<beans
    xmlns="https://jakarta.ee/xml/ns/jakartaee"
    xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
    xsi:schemaLocation="https://jakarta.ee/xml/ns/jakartaee https://jakarta.ee/xml/ns/jakartaee/beans_4_1.xsd"
>
</beans>

<!--

1. beans.xml file is responsible to create Beans, i.e. the Managed Classes on a Java EE project
2. There are 3 discovery modes : all, annotated, none
3. Using beans.xml file Java EE container will take the classes and make them available for Dependency Injection, whenever required
4. Equivalent Spring Boot : Java EE relation would be
   -> Container load: Spring IOC with @Bean, @Repository etc., Java EE IOC with ?
   -> Dependency Injection: Spring IOC using @Autowired, Java EE IOC using @Inject
   -> Life Cycle : Spring IOC [default, prototype, request & session], Java EE IOC ?
!-->